items.title: Segmentation Fault When Generating Field Masks For Protos with Optional Fields
items.body:
#### Environment details

  - OS type and version: gLinux
  - Python version: 3.7.0
  - pip version: 10.0.1
  - `google-api-core` version: 1.22.1
  - `protoc` version:  3.12.3

#### Steps to reproduce

  1.  Write the following to `foo.proto`:

```
syntax = "proto3";
 
message Nested {
  optional bool test = 1;
}
 
message Foo {
  optional string name = 1;
  Nested nested = 3;
}
```

  2. Compile with `protoc`: `protoc --experimental_allow_proto3_optional --python_out=. foo.proto`

  3. Write the following to `repro.py`:

```py
from foo_pb2 import Foo
from google.api_core import protobuf_helpers
 
foo = Foo()
foo.name = 'name'
foo.nested.test = False
 
field_mask = protobuf_helpers.field_mask(None, foo)
```

#### Code example

```python
# example
```
  4. Install latest `google-api-core`: `python -m pip install google-api-core`
  5. Run: `python repro.py`

#### Stack trace
Using `faulthandler`:

```
Fatal Python error: Segmentation fault

Current thread 0x00007eff5260d180 (most recent call first):
  File "/venvs/simply-local-3.7.0/lib/python3.7/site-packages/google/api_core/protobuf_helpers.py", line 314 in field_mask
  File "repro.py", line 9 in <module>
Segmentation fault
```

items.title: TypeError: 'float' object is not callable

labels.name: priority: p1
labels.description: Medium priority. Will be fixed prior to next release.

labels.name: type: bug
labels.description: Error or flaw in code with unintended results or allowing sub-optimal usage patterns.

items.body:
How to reproduce:
(1) clone [https://github.com/googleapis/python-cloudbuild](https://github.com/googleapis/python-cloudbuild) and checkout `sijun` branch.
(2) run `python -m nox -s unit-3.6 -- -s`

Exception thrown:
```
    def _apply_decorators(func, decorators):
        """Apply a list of decorators to a given function.
    
        ``decorators`` may contain items that are ``None`` or ``False`` which will
        be ignored.
        """
        decorators = filter(_is_not_none_or_false, reversed(decorators))
    
        for decorator in decorators:
>           func = decorator(func)
E           TypeError: 'float' object is not callable
```

Description of the bug:

`google.api_core.gapic_v1.method._GapicCallable.__call__` [calls](https://github.com/googleapis/python-api-core/blob/master/google/api_core/gapic_v1/method.py#L115) `_determine_timeout` to create an `timeout_` object, then passes it to `_apply_decorators(self._target, [retry, timeout_])`. 

In my example, `_determine_timeout(600.0, 600.0, None)` creates/returns `600.0`, which is a float object, when it is passed to `_apply_decorators`, the 'float' object is not callable is raised. 

`_determine_timeout` should always return a Timeout object.

Due to PR#29, we now see the following error:

'grpc.experimental.aio' has no attribute 'StreamUnaryCall'

items.title: [AsyncIO] Overview of gRPC AsyncIO integration

labels.name: type: feature request
labels.description: ‘Nice-to-have’ improvement, new feature or different behavior or design.

items.body:
AsyncIO introduces `async`/`await` keywords. In order to plumb through the asynchronous-ness of functions, the library has to expose `async` functions on its surface. So, while integrating gRPC AsyncIO, we might need to instrument following classes in order to make gRPC AsyncIO work.

Also, since `python-api-core` supports all Python versions, we can't use any `async`/`await` in existing modules. If needed, the import of new AsyncIO modules will be protected by explicit version check.

A all-in-one draft PR can be found: https://github.com/googleapis/python-api-core/pull/22.

- [x] google.api_core.async_future
- [x] google.api_core.gapic_v1.config_async
- [x] google.api_core.gapic_v1.method_async
- [x] google.api_core.operations_v1.operations_async_client
- [x] google.api_core.grpc_helpers_async
- [x] google.api_core.operation_async
- [x] google.api_core.retry_async

Unit tests included for all new modules under tests/asyncio.

For each module, I will create separate issues and PRs later.

items.title: Documentation for  "projectid" required when creating client using explicit credentials

labels.name: type: docs
labels.description: Improvement to the documentation for an API.

items.body:
Reference issue: https://github.com/googleapis/python-storage/issues/93

When user pass a explicit credential at the time of client creation, they forgot to pass `project_id`.
They were unable to find documentation regarding that. even example in documentation specify only credentials to pass like `client = Client(credentials=credentials)`.
     
Here is the documentation of  [explicit credentials](https://googleapis.dev/python/google-api-core/latest/auth.html#explicit-credentials).
/cc @crwilcox @busunkim96

items.title: add client_cert_source to ClientOptions

labels.name: type: feature request
labels.description: ‘Nice-to-have’ improvement, new feature or different behavior or design.

items.body: google-api-go-client uses `WithClientCertSource` in `ClientOptions` to provide client cert/key, we need to add a `client_cert_source` to `ClientOptions` in python as well.

items.title: client_options.from_dict should accept other mapping types

labels.name: type: feature request
labels.description: ‘Nice-to-have’ improvement, new feature or different behavior or design.

items.body:
Raised by @plamut  in https://github.com/googleapis/google-api-python-client/pull/829/.

> Is there a reason for accepting dicts only? Someone might prefer having the options stored in a different dict flavor, e.g. defaultdict, and accepting mappings in general would represent a usability improvement to them.

Documentation in this library needs to be updated. See https://googleapis.dev/python/google-api-core/latest/client_options.html 

Clients should also be updated to accept mapping types:
```
 if isinstance(client_options, six.moves.collections_abc.Mapping):
```

instead of

```
if type(client_options) == dict:
```

items.title: Core: Should not retry on INTERNAL

labels.name: type: question
labels.description: Request for information or clarification. Not an issue.

items.body:
According to AIP, [INTERNAL errors should not be retried](https://aip.dev/194).

This is a possible cause for a [Spanner client issue](https://github.com/googleapis/python-spanner/issues/4).
